5 Outputs
Write a survey input file for each estimand and its associated weight variable.

# Create an input file for each
for (i in seq_len(nrow(indicator_map))) {
  spec &lt;- indicator_map[i, ]

  indicator_file &lt;- survey_inputs |&gt;
    transmute(
      unit_id,
      domain_id = .data[[spec$id_col]],
      indicator = .data[[spec$indicator]],
      weight = .data[[spec$weight]]
    )

  write_csv(
    indicator_file,
    file.path(output_dir, str_c("ind_weight_", spec$indicator, ".csv"))
  )
}

Also export the domain sizes used by the estimand-specific input files.

write_csv(adult_domain_sizes_msoa, file.path(output_dir, "domain_sizes_adult_msoa.csv"))
write_csv(population_domain_sizes_la, file.path(output_dir, "domain_sizes_population_la.csv"))

So far, we have produced:

data/clean/domain_sizes_adult_msoa.csv, for adult population by MSOA (from Census 2021);
data/clean/domain_sizes_population_la.csv, for total resident population by LA (from Census 2021);
data/clean/ind_weight_commute_distance.csv, with analysis adult weight;
data/clean/ind_weight_poor_bus_satisfaction.csv, with grossing adult weight;
data/clean/ind_weight_walk_weekly.csv, with active-travel module weight scaled to LA total population;
